# My notes for pythonguis.com


# Creating your first app with PyQt6

QtWidgets contains a bunch of classes useful for creating an application.
QApplication: application handler, holds the event loop of application
QWidget: UI element

The main modules for Qt are QtWidgets, QtGui and QtCore.

app = QApplication(sys.argv)    # an instance of QApplication passing sys.argv(a list of command line arguments)
*import sys if you need sys.argv

In Qt, all top level widgets are windows

We need to call .show() for a window to be visible/ make it appear during application execution.

A window:
1. Holds application's UI
2. Every application needs at least one but can have more
3. Application exits when the last window is closed

Event loop: When the user interacts with our application, an event is generated and placed on the event queue.
The queue passes events to the even loop, if a waiting event is found, it is passed to the event handler.
Control passes back to the even loop to wait for more events and the process continues.
There can be only one running event loop per application.
QApplication class holds the Qt event loop.